        <h1>
             Type 1 and Type 2 Hypervisors
        </h1>

            <div style="text-align:center">
                <p>
                <img
                src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e1/Hyperviseur.png">
                </p>
            </div>

            <details>
                <summary id="sum1">
                    Type 1 Hypervisor
                </summary>
    
                <figure>
                <img src="graphics/07-01.jpg"
                    height="210" width="400">
                <figcaption>
                    Location of type 1 and 2 hypervisors.
                </figcaption>
                </figure>
                <p>
                Runs directly on the hardware.
                <br />
                This makes it essentially an OS.
                </p>

                <p>
                <iframe width="560" height="315"
                    src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/szhEiTOUt2s"
                    frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                <br />
                <i>Type 1 video</i>
                </p>

            </details>

            <details>
                <summary id="sum1">
                    Type 2 Hypervisor
                </summary>
    
                <figure>
                <img src="graphics/07-02.jpg"
                    height="180" width="550">
                <figcaption>
                Table of hypervisor examples.
                </figcaption>
                </figure>
                <p>
                This is a program that runs in an underlying OS. For example,
                Parallels runs on MacOS, and allows Windows or Linux to run on
                it.
                <br />
                <br />
                Also called <b>hosted hypervisors</b>.
                <br />
                <br />
                It installs a guest OS by pretending it is a machine being
                booted for the first time, and installing the OS from media,
                onto a "disk" (that is really an ordinary OS file).
                </p>

                <p>
                <iframe width="560" height="315"
                    src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/xTkvClJZmyA"
                    frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                <br />
                <i>Type 2 video</i>
                </p>

            </details>

